6.8 Question 8 — Type checking
For a random vector (A:R^d), distinguish the types of:

(A);
(aR^d);
((A));
({AB}), where (BB(R^d));
(E[ZA]).

6.2 Bridge 2
The collision argument is incomplete because:

the two points may both have probability zero;
one or both points may lie outside the support of (Z);
the collision may occur only on a null subset of latent space;
the conditional law given the shared observation may still be degenerate almost surely;
for continuous distributions, pointwise collisions do not by themselves establish positive conditional variance on a positive-probability set of observations.

The required claim is probabilistic, not merely set-theoretic.
